{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584834","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584834"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:58:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:58:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14816"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14816","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14816"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.92,0,0.04,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7507"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114061"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7507","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7507"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14816"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96076"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5122"},{"type":"tags","id":"7004"},{"type":"tags","id":"7601"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18353"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18355"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18425"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114061","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114061"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EGrowth hormone is produced by somatotroph cells in the anterior pituitary gland and affects multiple target tissues throughout the body, including bone, muscle, and liver.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary signaling method used by growth hormone?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Paracrine signaling","Endocrine signaling","Juxtacrine signaling","Intracrine signaling","Autocrine signaling"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGrowth hormone uses \u003Cstrong\u003Eendocrine signaling\u003C/strong\u003E, meaning it is secreted into the bloodstream and travels through circulation to reach distant target tissues where it exerts its effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParacrine signaling\u003C/strong\u003E involves communication between adjacent cells without entering the bloodstream, such as immune cells releasing cytokines that affect nearby cells. \u003Cstrong\u003EJuxtacrine signaling\u003C/strong\u003E requires direct physical contact between signaling and target cells, as seen in Notch signaling during development. \u003Cstrong\u003EIntracrine signaling\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when signals act within their cell of synthesis, such as vitamin D activation within kidney cells. \u003Cstrong\u003EAutocrine signaling\u003C/strong\u003E happens when cells produce signals that act back on themselves, as seen when cancer cells produce their own growth factors. As a classic endocrine hormone, growth hormone is released from the anterior pituitary and travels via the bloodstream to reach multiple target tissues throughout the body including bone, muscle, and liver cells.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Growth hormone is released from the anterior pituitary and travels via the bloodstream to act on distant target tissues.","Endocrine signaling involves hormone release into circulation to reach distant target organs.","Other signaling methods like paracrine, autocrine, and juxtacrine act locally rather than systemically."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRe